Yes, there are three radio buttons at the top of the image that control which of the three Moran's I values is displayed on the scatterplot. The radio buttons are labeled "Min", "Original", and "Max". The scatterplot shows the relationship between two variables, with one variable on the x-axis and the other variable on the y-axis. The points on the scatterplot are colored according to the value of the Moran's I statistic for that point. The Moran's I statistic measures the degree of spatial autocorrelation in the data. A high Moran's I value indicates that there is a strong positive spatial autocorrelation, meaning that points that are close together are more likely to have similar values. A low Moran's I value indicates that there is a strong negative spatial autocorrelation, meaning that points that are close together are more likely to have different values.
